# Pathogen Design System

Pathogen is the shared visual language for healthcare, laboratory, and public-health tools. It lives in components, tokens, previews, and CSS. The system is strongest when those pieces feel like one considered product.

On a busy screen, Pathogen should feel **quiet, precise, accessible, compact, and trustworthy**. The interface should make the work easier to see: the specimen row, the run status, the form error, the save action. Everything else should stay out of the way.

## The Five Qualities

| Quality | What it asks of the UI |
|---------|------------------------|
| **Quiet** | Surfaces recede. Colour and weight appear only when they carry meaning. |
| **Precise** | Type, spacing, corners, and alignment feel intentional at every scale. |
| **Accessible** | Focus, contrast, names, state, and motion are part of the form. |
| **Compact** | Dense tools keep enough rhythm for reading, scanning, and correction. |
| **Trustworthy** | Clinical work feels credible because the interface is clear and consistent. |

These qualities are not separate checkboxes. A compact grid is trustworthy only if it remains readable. A quiet button is accessible only if its state is still visible. Precision is what holds the whole system together.

## Influences

Pathogen borrows from Bauhaus, Dieter Rams, and the craft tradition behind products like Apple's. The useful lesson is not a visual costume. It is the belief that structure, use, material, and detail should feel inseparable.

**Bauhaus gives us structure.** Shape follows use. Alignment, proportion, and repeated parts do more work than decoration. In Pathogen, that means a 4px rhythm, rectangular controls, clear dividers, simple geometry, and asymmetry only when the workflow itself has unequal weight.

**Rams gives us restraint.** Less is better when what remains is clearer. Product surfaces should rely on borders, layers, and state before shadow, glow, or expressive colour.

**Craft gives us care.** Good UI feels obvious because many small decisions agree: labels line up, focus rings are visible, disabled controls behave honestly, and token choices match the component's job. The details users do not name are still part of the experience.

## From Smallest Part To Whole Product

Build from purpose, then move outward:

```text
Purpose
  What job does this element do?
    ↓
Tokens
  Colour, type, radius, elevation, motion
    ↓
Building blocks
  Roles, scale, spacing, corners, state
    ↓
Controls
  Button, link, form field, tab
    ↓
Content
  Labels, body copy, code, copyable values, tooltips
    ↓
Surfaces
  Panels, grids, fieldsets, dialogs, overlays
    ↓
Pages
  Regions, workflows, host apps, previews
```

| Layer | Examples | Read more |
|-------|----------|-----------|
| Tokens | `--pvc-color-surface`, `--type-control` | [Tokens](<%= page_path("design-system-tokens") %>) |
| Building blocks | Colour roles, type scale, spacing, radius | [Foundations](<%= page_path("design-system-design-contract") %>) |
| Controls | `Button`, `Link`, `Form::*` | [Foundations](<%= page_path("design-system-design-contract") %>) |
| Surfaces | `DataGridComponent`, fieldsets, dialogs | [Foundations](<%= page_path("design-system-design-contract") %>), [Dark mode](<%= page_path("design-system-dark-mode") %>) |
| Pages | Host apps, Lookbook previews | [Preview guidelines](<%= page_path("design-system-preview-guidelines") %>) |

The [Foundations](<%= page_path("design-system-design-contract") %>) page describes how the middle layers behave: colour, type, spacing, radius, elevation, motion, controls, and accessibility.

## Surfaces, Not Cards

A **surface** is a bounded work area: a grid frame, form section, fieldset, dialog body, or preview frame. It has a job. It groups related work, separates one region from another, or contains a focused task.

Pathogen does not ship a generic `Card` component yet. Compose surfaces from tokens and layout. The `:card` preset on `Pathogen::Typography::HeadingGroup` is only a compact heading style, not a card component.

